        // (1,1) -> (2,2) (D)
        // Total 3 moves. 2 diagonal.
        // This is `n + (k-m) - 1` if we just change one diagonal move to an axial move.
        // No, this is `n + (k-m) - 2` because we need to change the parity of the path.
        // If `k-m` is odd, we need to make `k-m` extra moves.
        // We can use `(k-m-1)/2` pairs of (1,1) and (-1,-1) moves. This adds `k-m-1` diagonal moves.
        // This leaves 1 move. This 1 move must be an axial move.
        // To accommodate this, we must change one of the existing diagonal moves into an axial move.
        // For example, instead of (0,0) -> (1,1) (1 move, 1 diag), we do (0,0) -> (1,0) -> (1,1) (2 moves, 0 diag).
